[normal] whereby immigrants devote themselves more to education than the native population because they lack financial c
[normal]apital and see education as a way out of poverty
[normal].
[normal] The inverse of this is true for W
[normal]hite British and Black Caribbean WC 
[normal]students: 
[normal]l
[normal]ow
[normal]er
[normal] educational aspirations
[normal] by parents and students
[normal], poor ASC and low motivation 
[normal]indicates an increased risk of dis
[normal]engaged or
[normal] 
[normal]disaffect
[normal]ed
[normal] learners
[normal]. 
[normal]In the era 
[normal]of full employment
[normal] there may have been little 
[normal]penalty
[normal] 
[normal]to disengagement 
[normal]where jobs were plentiful
[normal],
[normal] often through family contacts
[normal],
[normal] without the need for educational qualifications. However there is a high cost to an 
[normal]‘oppositi
[normal]onal culture’ 
[normal](Willis, 1977) 
[normal]in 
[normal]the 
[normal]new knowledge economy.
[normal]12. It is important not to over-emphasise 
[normal]an
[normal] individualistic notion 
[normal]of 
[normal]aspirations and to recognise structural influences from 
[normal]neighbourhood
[normal], family and school. It is not enough for young people to aspire, they also need to be able to navigate the paths to their goals
[normal] (Strand &amp; Winston, 2008)
[normal]. There is an important role for s
[normal]chools
[normal], particularly in disadvantaged areas,
[normal] in supporting 
[normal]students and 
[normal]parents
[normal] by providing clear information on 
[normal]how a minimum number of GCSEs are required for most college courses, work-based learning settings and 'decent' jobs, greater supervision of ho
[normal]mework by teachers
[normal] 
[normal]to minimise the risk that student disengage as a result of falling behind and feeling overwhelmed by coursework, provision of additional study support
[normal], close monitoring of student truancy etc. 
[normal](e.g. Ross, 2009)
[normal].
[normal]13. 
[normal]However it is importa
[normal]nt that addressing low educational attainment 
[normal]is not just a question of disengagement age 11-16 or 
[normal]an 
[normal]issue 
[normal]just 
[normal]for secondary schools. 
[normal]T
[normal]he low achievem
[normal]ent of White British students on
[normal] FSM 
[normal]has been
[normal] identif
[normal]i
[normal]ed as early as age 4, and these students fall furt
[normal]her behind age 4-7 (Strand, 1999), age 7-11 (Strand, 
[normal]2010, 
[normal]2014b) as well as age 11-16 (Strand, 2014a). In short equity differences in achievement are just as much a concern for primary schooling as for secondary schooling. 
[normal]14. 
[normal]It is also important that s
[normal]chools are not seen as the sole agencies 
[normal]of
[normal] change.
[normal] 
[normal]Differences between schools, while they undoubtedly play some role, a
[normal]ppear
[normal] unlikely to be the major locus of equity gaps in pupils’ educational progress. 
[normal]Strand (2010) reports an analysis of pupil progres
[normal]s age 7-11 using national data from 534,000 pupils attending over 14,000 primary schools. 
[normal]While the SES and the White British-Black Caribbean gaps widen between age 7 and age 11, these gaps do not appear to be significantly greater
[normal] in some schools than in 
[normal]others
[normal]. 
[normal]No schools reliably reversed the usual ‘within school’ pattern of FSM students making less progress than non-FSM students, or Black Caribbean students making less progress than White British students.
[normal] 
[normal]This has two major implications:
[normal]i
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal] Equity gaps are not the result of a small number of 'failing' schools which, if they can somehow be fixed, will remove
[normal] the overall SES or ethnic achievement 
[normal]gaps. 
[normal]While qualitative research has provided case studies of schools in disadvantaged areas that 
[normal]‘succeed 
[normal]against the odds’ (e.g. 
[normal]DCSF Extra Mile project, 2008), such schools are by definition exceptions. As Mortimore and Whitty (1997) observe “whilst some schools can succeed against the odds, the possibility of them all doing so, year in and year out
[normal], still appears remote given that the long-term patterning of educational inequality has been strikingly consistent throughout the history of public education in most countries” (p9).  Similarly in the US Rothstein (2004) has cogently argued that, exemplar
[normal]y though such schools might be, they do not represent scalable models for Americ
[normal]a’s poor and minority children.
[normal] 
[normal]ii
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]Neither is a 
[normal]focus on 
[normal]general 
[normal]'
[normal]school improvement
[normal]'
[normal] suffic
[normal]i
[normal]ent. While the most effective schools 
[normal]do 
[normal]raise the achievement of disadvantaged p
[normal]upil
[normal]s, non-disadvantaged pupils tend to 
[normal]benefit just as much, so that these school do not eliminate the achievement gap. 
[normal]The correlation between a schools' residual (i.e. difference from the expected value) for FSM pupils correlated 0.97 with the school
[normal]s'
[normal] 
[normal]residual for non-FSM pupils. The results are shown in Figure 4. Thus p
[normal]rimary schools that added the most value for White British students, girls or those not on FSM also added the most value for Black Caribbean students, boys or pupils on FSM
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]In short the
[normal] relative performance of the disadvantaged remains similar even when the absolute performance of such groups has improved (Mortimore &amp; Whitty, 1997; Strand, 2010, 2014b).
[normal]Figure 4: Correlation of [bold]primary schools' Contextual Value Added (CVA) residuals [bold]for [bold]pupils entitled to FSM and those not [bold]entitled to [bold]FSM[bold]Source: Strand (2010).
[normal]15. These results do not deny the possibility that processes occuring
[normal] within schools and classrooms may contribute to the poor progress of disadvantaged pupils or some ethnic minority groups, but does imply that such processes would need to be operating consistently across all schools. For example recent research suggests t
[normal]hat setting is on the rise within primary schools in England, with a recent nationally representative survey indicating that over one-third of children in Y2 were set in literacy, mathematics or both, and that
[normal] 
[normal]low SES children were disproportionally repres
[normal]ented in bottom sets  (Hallam &amp; Ireson, 2013). Setting has been hypothesised to increase within school gaps for disadvantaged and ethnic minority students (
[normal]e.g. 
[normal]Wiliam &amp; Bartholomew, 200
[normal]4; Oakes, 2005
[normal]). Another possible candidate is the distribution of tea
[normal]chers across classrooms 
[normal]within
[normal] schools, with research from the US indicating that Black and disadvantaged students were more likely to be matched to novice teachers while more highly qualified teachers were matched to White and more advantaged students (Cl
[normal]otfelter, Ladd &amp; Vigor, 2005). They suggest this reflects both pressure from more affluent parents to secure better resources for their children and the greater power of more experienced teachers to lobby for more easy-to-educate students
[normal].
[normal]16. [bold]The key impl[bold]ication of the [bold]above is that[bold] [bold]all[bold] schools need to focus on their 'within-school' gaps and that [bold]i[bold]ntervention[bold]s[bold] [bold]need to be [bold]targeted[bold] at disadvantaged students[bold].[bold] This is the great hope for the Pupil Premium. 
[normal]This delivers greater funding to schools 
[normal]with high prop
[normal]ortions of disadvantaged students 
[normal]in a transparent manner. 
[normal]It also comes with t
[normal]he 
[normal]expectation
[normal] that 
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]grant will be used to support FSM eligible pupils, should focus on 
[normal]clos
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]the gap
[normal] in attainment
[normal] between them and their peers,
[normal] and 
[normal]accountability measures such as 
[normal]the publication of the FSM gap in
[normal] school performance tables (
[normal] although it is 
[normal]important that schools are accountable for the 
[normal]progress
[normal] of their students not for 'raw' attainment ou
[normal]tcomes
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]17. 
[normal]S
[normal]ince the demise of grammar school system 
[normal]in the late 1960's 
[normal]educational policy in England 
[normal]has
[normal], for good reason, 
[normal] been wary of differentiat
[normal]ing educational provision 
[normal]at 
[normal]too early 
[normal]an age 
[normal]for fear of 
[normal]exacerbating social 
[normal]inequality. 
[normal]Certainly
[normal] sorting
[normal] students into separate schools at age 11 or age 14 is to be avoided
[normal], since the 
[normal]evidence suggests this 
[normal]such differentiation tends to reproduce social
[normal] inequality rather than eliminate it (e.g. Willis, 1977)
[normal]. 
[normal]Nevertheless the evidence on disengagement of WWC students, particularly age 14-16, 
[normal]reviewed in Section 4 above 
[normal]suggests that providing all students with the same curriculum in KS4 fails to meet the
[normal] 
[normal]desire
[normal] of a significant minority for 
[normal]learning that makes a strong connection between the academic and the world of work. It i
[normal]s a matter of some regret that the statutory duty of schools to provide work related learning (WRL) 
[normal]at KS4 
[normal]was removed in Septembe
[normal]r 2012. 
[normal]T
[normal]he raising of the school leaving age to 17 
[normal]in 
[normal]Septemb
[normal]er
[normal] 2012
[normal], and to age 18 in September 2015, 
[normal]may move a
[normal]ttention 
[normal]to 
[normal]16-19
[normal] years olds
[normal], but strong programme
[normal]s
[normal] of WRL at KS4 should continue to be a focus for all schools, particularly
[normal] those 
[normal]serving 
[normal]disadvantaged communities
